abstract: WILKESBARRE, Penn., Aug. 1. -- The town of Warrior Run, near here, is threatened with destruction as a result of a terrific explosion which occurred tonight. Gases are escaping from the Warrior Run Mine through crevices in the earth and the panic-stricken inhabitants will not have any lights in their houses for fear they may cause explosions. As a consequence the town is in total darkness.

abstract: MILAN, Italy, Aug. 3. -- The loss by fire on the buildings and exhibits of the International Exposition early this morning is estimated at a sum between $2,000,000 and $3,000,000. The fire started in the Palace of Decorative Arts, which covered 15,000 square yards and contained 4,000 exhibits. The structure is now a mass of ruins, and the exhibits, chiefly fine examples of furniture, hangings, household goods, and clothing, are a total loss.

abstract: WAWBEEK, N.Y., Aug. 4. -- Trips by water in the Adirondacks are becoming the popular mode of travel, and the number of touring parties are increasing daily. abstract: A letter on July 30 in commendation of the recent paving of lower Broadway with wooden blocks arouses the question why this pavement is not more generally used. It lessens the noise 50 per cent. and it is more easily repaired than asphalt. Our severe Winters may be hard on it, but in Paris, where it is used exclusively, there are also extremes of heat and cold, though in periods of shorter duration.

abstract: SARATOGA, Aug. 8. -- Although all the gambling houses were closed to-day, gambling was going on in secret. Only games which required simple paraphernalia were conducted. Faro was dealt in secluded hotel rooms, while poker games were numerous. One poker game, which caused talk among the men fond of high play, was played in a Broadway hotel. A single "pot" in the early afternoon, it is said, had $5,000 in it.

abstract: PITTSBURG, Aug. 8. -- Clinton B. Wray, former teller of the Union Trust Company, who with C.S. Hixton, individual bookkeeper, is accused of robbing the bank of between $125,000 and $300,000, will be brought back to-morrow from Toronto, Canada, where he was arrested with Grace Loughrey. Wray's arrest brings to light that he fled once before, fearing arrest, and also the fact that the scheme that was worked was one which almost defied detection.

abstract: MAY I sat just a word or two more on the Keats Memorial in Rome? abstract: LONG BEACH, L.I., Aug. 13. -- Rudolf Heilman of 463 Clermont Avenue, Brooklyn, was drowned in sight of his wife and twelve-year-old daughter at Point Lookout Beach yesterday afternoon. abstract: BASTOGNE, Belgium, Aug. 13. -- Duray, driving a De Dietrich car, won the international automobile race to-day over the historic Ardennes course. He averaged 106 kilometers an hour, (about 65 1/2 miles,) establishing a new world's record for a long-distance motor race. Henriot, driving a Darracq, was second; Rougier, De Dietrich, third; Barillier, Brasier, fourth; Gabriel, De Dietrich, fifth, and Clement, Bayard-Clement, sixth.

abstract: WORCESTER. Mass., Aug. 13. -- The fight for next year's National rowing regatta promises to be interesting. During the annual event here last week there was a deal of booming for certain localities, the Philadelphia contingent being very much in evidence. abstract: I find in to-day's TIMES a letter from Mr. Bradley Garretson, alleging that "the Garretsons all came from Holland about 1716 not 1816." Doubtless it will gratify him to learn that the family is much longer established in this country than he supposes. A Garretson family, I believe from Holland, settled in Kings County early in the seventeenth century and the early records of Kings County have many references to their doings.

abstract: Australia is regulating our trusts for us. That is the significance of the telegram announcing that the Federal customs on agricultural implements have been increased from 12 1/2 per cent to 25 per cent. It will be seen how very different the method is from our own. We regulate railway tariffs, and the Australians regulate the customs, but the result is the same, for both factors are elements of cost to the consumer.

abstract: The full report of the country's foreign commerce for last July shows that all previous records for that month were exceeded, despite the falling off in the exports of domestic products reported earlier in the week. abstract: BAR HARBOR, Me., Aug. 21. -- The seventh annual Bar Harbor Horse Show brought out the largest field of entries for years to-day, and in quality of exhibits has never been equaled. The stables of Philip Livingston carried off several blue ribbons, but, on the whole, the awards were well scattered.

abstract: PEEKSKILL, N.Y., Aug. 22. -- The Democratic convention for the Third Assembly District of Westchester County, which was held in Cryptic Lodge Hall in Peekskill this afternoon, resulted in the delegates being sent to the State Convention unpledged. David Anderson of Montroseon-the-Hudson offered a resolution indorsing Hearst, and there was considerable applause.

abstract: Fire Commissioner John H. O'Brien sent in his first report yesterday as head of the Fire Department. The paper opens with the statement that the department in the past year made the greatest stride in its history. Four new companies were organized in Manhattan and the Bronx. In Richmond fourteen companies were organized and six in Queens. The uniformed force now numbers 3,554 men, an increase of 402 for the year.

abstract: At Portland Mr. BEVERIDGE lifted up his eloquent voice against "exclusively private control of our transportation system." abstract: The Nebraska delegation to the Bryan reception arrived in Jersey City over the Pennsylvania Railroad last night, nearly five hours late. The special train was due at 6:15 o'clock, and arrived at 10:30 o'clock. The delegates, who number 120, were so weary from the long ride that they were glad to get over to the Hotel Victoria, where seventy rooms had been engaged for them.

abstract: Silverware and articles made of plated silver, britannia metal, pewter, copper, brass, and bronze are advancing in price because of the increased cost of metal. The manufacturers of silverware are anxiously watching the result of the Government's action in resuming the purchase of silver bullion. They say that any further advance in the price of the white metal will necessitate new price lists all around for the coming holiday trade.

abstract: BOSTON, Aug. 26. -- Sylvester B. Hinckley, President of the First National Bank of Chelsea, which closed its doors Aug. 17, died to-day at his home at Newton, in his sixty-fifth year. abstract: OMAHA, Aug. 28. -- W.R. abstract: Most of the first class hotels in the city were full to their capacity last night, and travelers who had not reserved their rooms ahead had to drive about in cabs for an hour before they could find accommodation. abstract: In the expectation that there would be thousands of persons seeking entrance to Madison Square Garden to hear William J. Bryan last night, 778 policemen, under ten Captains and three Inspectors, were stationed about the big hall and in the surrounding streets. Throughout the evening they formed the greater part of the throng about the place where Mr. Bryan was speaking, and at no time was the presence of half that number of policemen necessary.

abstract: READVILLE, Mass., Aug. 30 -- The pacing event for the fast horses was again the feature of the Grand Circuit meet at the Readville track to-day and four of the racers were well bunched in all three heats, Gratt winning from Baron Gratton in each event by a head. While no records were broken, the times were fast.

abstract: According to the Washington dispatches President Roosevelt has consented to make use of his official position and the authority of the Government to push toward what is called the simplified spelling movement. It is a scheme financed by Andrew Carnegie, backed by certain large publishing interests, and designed to carry out an immense project for jobbery in reprinting dictionaries and school books, which will cost the people millions of dollars.
